{{afc comment|1=This page was originally created in the draft namespace on english wikipedia. It was then deleted but preserved on everybodywiki. The imported history from everybodywiki is patchwork and contains all the contributing users, but not all the revisions are actually present. Lets hope this is sufficient attribution though especially since most of them are mine.[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 08:28, 2 May 2025 (UTC)}}
{{ill|Tokyo Ten Shrines|ja|東京十社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Ten Shrines|qq=}} are a group of ten prominent shrines in tokyo
==List==
* {{ill|Hakusan Shrine (Bunkyo Ward)|ja|白山神社 (文京区)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan Shrine (Bunkyo Ward)|qq=}} * [[Hie Shrine]] * [[Hikawa Shrine (Akasaka)]]
* [[Kameido Tenjin Shrine]] * [[Kanda Shrine]]
* [[Nezu Shrine]]
* [[Ōji Shrine]] * {{ill|Shiba Dai-jingū|pl|4=ja|5=芝大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiba Dai-jingū|qq=}} * {{ill|Shinagawa-jinja|ja|品川神社|pl|Shinagawa-jinja|1=Shinagawa Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinagawa-jinja|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinagawa Shrine|qq=}}
* [[Tomioka Hachiman Shrine]]
'''Tokyo Jissha''' (東京十社) refers to ten shrines located around Tokyo selected in 1975 from among the original twelve {{ill|Jun-Chokusai-sha|ja|准勅祭社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jun-Chokusai-sha|qq=}}.
== Overview == Following the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]] and {{ill|Tokyo Tento|ja|東京奠都|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Tento|qq=}}, Emperor Meiji decreed the annual festival of [[:en:Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine (Minato-ku, Tokyo)]] as a Chokusai (Imperial festival) on October 17, 1868. Subsequently, on November 8 of the same year, major shrines around Tokyo were designated as Jun-Chokusai-sha (Semi-Imperial Shrines), joining the historical [[:en:Twenty-Two Shrines|Twenty-Two Shrines]] in Kinai as protectors of Tokyo and promoters of public welfare.
Originally, there were twelve Jun-Chokusai-sha: {{ill|Hie Shrine (Chiyoda)|ja|日枝神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hie Shrine (Chiyoda)|qq=}}, [[:en:Nezu Shrine|Nezu Shrine]], {{ill|Shiba Daijingu|ja|芝大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiba Daijingu|qq=}}, {{ill|Kanda Shrine|ja|神田神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanda Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Hakusan Shrine (Bunkyo)|ja|白山神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan Shrine (Bunkyo)|qq=}}, [[:en:Kameido Tenjin Shrine|Kameido Tenjin Shrine]], {{ill|Shinagawa Shrine|ja|品川神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinagawa Shrine|qq=}}, [[:en:Tomioka Hachiman Shrine|Tomioka Hachimangu]], {{ill|Oji Shrine (Kita-ku, Tokyo)|ja|王子神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oji Shrine (Kita-ku, Tokyo)|qq=}}, {{ill|Akasaka Hikawa Shrine|ja|赤坂氷川神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akasaka Hikawa Shrine|qq=}}, [[:en:Ōkunitama Shrine|Okunitama Shrine]] (Rokusho Shrine), and [[:en:Washinomiya Shrine|Washinomiya Shrine]]. However, the system was abolished on September 1, 1870, and these shrines were reclassified under different Ranks. Shrine Rankings themselves were abolished entirely after World War II. Notably, the original "Shinagawa Shrine" designation might have referred to the current {{ill|Ebara Shrine|ja|荏原神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebara Shrine|qq=}}, previously known as Shinagawa Kifune Shrine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ebarajinja.org/jyunchoku/index.html|title=Ebara Shrine - Jun-Chokusai-sha|accessdate=2021-1-6}}</ref> Currently, both Shinagawa Shrine and Ebara Shrine claim their historical status as Jun-Chokusai-sha, though only Shinagawa Shrine is included in the "Tokyo Jissha Meguri" pilgrimage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-jinjacho.or.jp/shinagawa/5264/|title=Shinagawa Shrine|publisher=Tokyo Shrine Agency|accessdate=2021-1-6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokyo-jinjacho.or.jp/shinagawa/200137/|title=Ebara Shrine|publisher=Tokyo Shrine Agency|accessdate=2021-1-6}}</ref>
In 1975, commemorating the 50th anniversary of Emperor Showa's accession, shrines agreed to exclude the distant Okunitama Shrine in Fuchu and Washinomiya Shrine in Kuki, Saitama, establishing the "Tokyo Jissha Meguri," which today remains popular among visitors alongside other tours like the Seven Lucky Gods pilgrimage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jinjya.com/sp/101215.php|title=Tokyo Jissha Meguri Guide|accessdate=2016-12-24}}</ref>
== List of Tokyo Jissha == None of these shrines are listed in the ancient {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=}} registry. "Modern" indicates Ranks in the Meiji-era shrine classification system, and "Beppyo" indicates shrines listed as [[:en:Beppyo shrine|Beppyo Shrine]] after WWII.
